  },
  {
    "id": "R84_40",
    "content": "Use the query constructor function to declare a query in Convex.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_41",
    "content": "Queries accept named arguments. The argument values are accessible as fields of the second parameter of the handler function.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_42",
    "content": "To declare the types of arguments and validate them, add an args object using v validators.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_43",
    "content": "Queries can return values of any supported Convex type which will be automatically serialized and deserialized.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_44",
    "content": "When a query returns undefined it is translated to null on the client.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_45",
    "content": "To fetch from the database use the db field in the query context.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_46",
    "content": "To return URLs to stored files use the storage field in the query context.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_47",
    "content": "To check user authentication use the auth field in the query context.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Quality Assurance",
    "second_level": "Security Practices"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_48",
    "content": "You can define and call helper functions to split up query code or reuse logic across multiple Convex functions.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Architecture & Design",
    "second_level": "Design Principles & Patterns"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_49",
    "content": "You can export helpers to use them across multiple files. They will not be callable from outside of your Convex functions.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Architecture & Design",
    "second_level": "Design Principles & Patterns"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_50",
    "content": "Queries can import NPM packages installed in node_modules. Not all NPM packages are supported.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Development Workflow & Project Management",
    "second_level": "Dependency Management"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_51",
    "content": "To call a query from React use the useQuery hook along with the generated api object.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_52",
    "content": "Mutations insert, update and remove data from the database, check authentication or perform other business logic, and optionally return a response to the client application.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_53",
    "content": "When a mutation returns undefined it is translated to null on the client.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_54",
    "content": "Actions can call third party services to do things such as processing a payment with Stripe. They can interact with the database indirectly by calling queries and mutations.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Architecture & Design",
    "second_level": "System Architecture"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_55",
    "content": "HTTP actions allow you to build an HTTP API right in Convex! HTTP actions are exposed at https://<your deployment name>.convex.site.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Architecture & Design",
    "second_level": "System Architecture"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_56",
    "content": "The first argument to the handler is an ActionCtx object, which provides auth, storage, and scheduler, as well as runQuery, runMutation, runAction.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_57",
    "content": "The second argument contains the Request data. HTTP actions do not support argument validation, as the parsing of arguments from the incoming Request is left entirely to you.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_58",
    "content": "Convex allows you to schedule functions to run in the future. This allows you to build powerful durable workflows without the need to set up and maintain queues or other infrastructure.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Architecture & Design",
    "second_level": "System Architecture"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_59",
    "content": "runAfter schedules a function to run after a delay (measured in milliseconds).",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_60",
    "content": "runAt schedules a function run at a date or timestamp (measured in milliseconds elapsed since the epoch).",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_61",
    "content": "Every scheduled function is reflected as a document in the \"_scheduled_functions\" system table.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Architecture & Design",
    "second_level": "System Architecture"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_62",
    "content": "You can read data from system tables using the db.system.get and db.system.query methods, which work the same as the standard db.get and db.query methods.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_63",
    "content": "Cron jobs can be used to clean up data at a regular interval, send a reminder email at the same time every month, or schedule a backup every Saturday.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Architecture & Design",
    "second_level": "System Architecture"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_64",
    "content": "crons.interval() runs a function every specified number of seconds, minutes, or hours.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_65",
    "content": "crons.cron() the traditional way of specifying cron jobs by a string with five fields separated by spaces (e.g. \"* * * * *\"). Times in cron syntax are in the UTC timezone.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_66",
    "content": "crons.hourly(), crons.daily(), crons.weekly(), crons.monthly() provide an alternative syntax for common cron schedules with explicitly named arguments.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_67",
    "content": "File Storage makes it easy to implement file upload in your app, store files from and send files to third-party APIs, and to serve dynamic files to your users. All file types are supported.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Architecture & Design",
    "second_level": "System Architecture"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_68",
    "content": "Arbitrarily large files can be uploaded directly to your backend using a generated upload URL.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Architecture & Design",
    "second_level": "System Architecture"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_69",
    "content": "An upload URL can be generated by the storage.generateUploadUrl function of the MutationCtx object.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_70",
    "content": "The upload URL expires in 1 hour and so should be fetched shortly before the upload is made.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Quality Assurance",
    "second_level": "Security Practices"
  },
  {
    "id": "R84_71",
    "content": "Since the storage ID is returned to the client it is likely you will want to persist it in the database via another mutation.",
    "project": "tomredman_socialbutterfly",
    "file": ".cursorrules_raw",
    "first_level": "Code Implementation",
    "second_level": "Framework Usage"
  }
]
